  "translation": "Nonviolence, truthfulness, absence of anger, renunciation, peace, avoidance of fault-finding, compassion, freedom from greed, gentleness, modesty, and steadiness—these are divine qualities.",
  "purport": `
    <p><strong>1. Ethical Alignment — ‘ahiṁsā’, ‘satyam’, ‘akrodhaḥ’:</strong> Krishna begins with <em>ahiṁsā</em> (nonviolence), <em>satyam</em> (truthfulness), and <em>akrodhaḥ</em> (absence of anger), which together form the ethical foundation of conduct. Nonviolence extends beyond physical harm to include thought and intention, truthfulness aligns expression with reality, and absence of anger reflects mastery over emotional प्रतिक्रिया. These qualities ensure that interaction with others is guided by awareness rather than impulse.</p>

    <p><strong>2. Inner Renunciation and Peace — ‘tyāgaḥ’, ‘śhāntiḥ’:</strong> The terms <em>tyāgaḥ</em> (renunciation) and <em>śhāntiḥ</em> (peace) indicate an inward withdrawal from attachment and agitation. Renunciation here is not abandonment of action but release of possessiveness, allowing the mind to remain undisturbed. Peace arises naturally when the mind is no longer driven by constant desire and resistance.</p>

    <p><strong>3. Compassion and Non-Exploitation — ‘dayā bhūteṣu’, ‘aloluptvam’:</strong> Compassion toward all beings (<em>dayā bhūteṣu</em>) reflects recognition of shared existence, while <em>aloluptvam</em> (freedom from greed) prevents exploitation. Together, they create a mode of living that is harmonious and non-intrusive, where interaction is based on understanding rather than consumption.</p>

    <p><strong>4. Softness and Stability — ‘mārdavam’, ‘hrīḥ’, ‘achāpalam’:</strong> The qualities of gentleness (<em>mārdavam</em>), modesty (<em>hrīḥ</em>), and steadiness (<em>achāpalam</em>) reflect a balanced personality. Gentleness prevents harshness, modesty limits ego expansion, and steadiness ensures consistency. These qualities stabilize behavior and create a composed presence.</p>

    <p><strong>Conclusion:</strong> Verse 2 expands the description of divine qualities into ethical and emotional dimensions. By cultivating <em>ahiṁsā</em>, <em>tyāgaḥ</em>, and <em>dayā</em>, the individual aligns with a mode of living that is both internally peaceful and externally harmonious, reinforcing the integration of knowledge and action.</p>
  `
